      				<div class='pad'>

	        				        			
	        				        			
	        				        				<h1 class="title">
	        					Tuesday, June 10, 2008 - Up to the farm and a Conversation about Electricity	        				</h1>
	        				        			
	        				        			
	        				        			
	        				        			
	        				        			
	        			<div id="node-134" class="node ntype-blog">

  
  
      <span class="submitted">Tue, 2008-06-17 10:32 — VFC</span>
  
  <div class="meta">
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <p>It was lovely to finally get to the coffee farm. It is about a 1 1/2 hour drive from Comayagua, faster now that the road to the small rural community of San Jeronimo is paved. From there we leave the pavement and head up a very rough gravel and dirt road, crossing several mountain streams, moving slowly over rocky or rutted patches where the road has been worn away after rain. Working our way up, down, around and then up again into the mountains. As we get higher the temperature cools and the forest gets greener and more tropical until finally we turn the corner and see the farm house. It was great to be back again, surrounded by lush life of the mountains.</p><p><img src="../files/vfamily/u4/016.jpg" alt="" width="341" height="256" align="left" />We stayed up late in the kitchen talking with Abilio and his wife Bertilia. A major topic of conversation was the electrical poles and cables we had seen on our way up the mountain. Electricity has finally arrived just a few months ago to some of the communities below and there are plans to bring it further to the community of Los Planes maybe 20 minutes drive from the farm. There are mixed feelings about this sign of progress. Yes it would be great to have electricity for a few light bulbs, maybe a refrigerator. But this electricity the government is finally bringing is produced by conventional means using petroleum. There are renewable alternatives available - small hydroelectric projects using the water in the mountain streams or solar panels. The Rio Negro school already has two solar panels that are used to power a few computers, and now increasingly cell phones that are becoming very prevalent in the community. One neighbor who has very little education, figured out more than 10 years ago how to power a small generator by channeling water from the river through high pressure tubes to a small turbine. Abilio would like to develop the same kind of system for their property and for the community at large and has experimented a bit with limited success. In the meantime, we use candles most nights to move around(it is dark usually by 6:30 as the sun sets early behind the mountains). Although this first night of our visit, Abilio hooked his car battery up to a converter that is wired to a few light bulbs throughout the house to help us move around more easily.</p>  </div>
  
      <div class="links"><ul class="links inline"><li class="blog_usernames_blog first"><a href="../blog/4" title="Read VFC&#039;s latest blog entries.">VFC&#039;s blog</a></li>
